folder: Remsen Street & Henry Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
102 Remsen Street, at the S.E. corner of Henry Street, showing the Thomas Hunt house, later known as the Alexander E. Orr home. (Alexander Ector Orr was at one time President of the New York Chamber of Commerce, and was also President of the New York Produce Exchange for several terms). It was demolished in 1934.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Remsen Street & Henry Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
128-138 Remsen Street, south side, between Henry and Clinton Streets, showing from left to right beginning with the first stairway, the homes of Mrs. Haslett, Isaac Harding Frothingham, and the home of one Carey. No. 128 is the last completely shown home at the right.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Henry Street & Remsen Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Henry Street, east side, south from Remsen Street. In the center is Hunt's Mansion. In the extreme left foreground, is a section of the Church of the Pilgrims.

May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Remsen Street & Henry Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Remsen Street, north side, west from Henry Street. At extreme right foreground, a corner of the Church of the Pilgrim's.

August 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Henry Street & Remsen Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
(1)
Henry Street at Remsen Street, showing on the N.E. corner the Church of the Pilgrims. On the S.E. corner is a 4-story structure No. 100 Remsen Street. This is also a general view in a southwesterly direction.

March 1, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, showing in the foreground, a limited view of the south side of Montague Street. In the background, across the skyline from right to left are the Hotel St. George and the Temple Bar Building.

March 1, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.
